This article provides an update on the United States' response to the earthquake in Haiti in January. President Obama pledged a swift and aggressive effort to save lives and support the recovery in Haiti. The US deployed over 20,000 civilian and military personnel to carry out various activities such as search and rescue operations, restoring airports and ports, providing healthcare services, and meeting the basic needs of the Haitian people. The US also pledged $1.15 billion for Haiti's reconstruction and established the Clinton Bush Haiti Fund to raise additional funds. The US has been supportive of Haiti's efforts to establish the Interim Haiti Recovery Commission, which will coordinate development projects and priorities. The US has made significant contributions in areas such as search and rescue, restoring airports and ports, healthcare, food and water aid, shelter, and trade opportunities. The US has also prioritized activities that benefit the local Haitian economy and has provided coordination and communication support to relief efforts.